comment_text:
Beste,

Ik vernam van dierenrechtenor
ganisatie GAIA dat uw merk nog steeds kangoeroeleder gebruikt. Ik ben verbaasd en ontgoocheld.

De kangoeroejacht vindt 's nachts plaats, vanop grote afstanden, op bewegende doelwitten. Schoten die niet tot de onmiddellijke dood leiden, zijn onvermijdelijk.
Omdat jagers er vaak niet in slagen het dier onmiddellijk te doden, veroorzaken de schotwonden heel veel leed. Gewonde dieren slagen er soms in te ontsnappen en zijn veroordeeld tot een lange lijdensweg. Erger nog, kogels kunnen de keel, kaak, neus of oren raken.

Ondanks de recente bosbranden in Australi√´ gaat de kangoeroejacht gewoon verder. Het jachtquotum voor 2020 is vastgelegd op 6 miljoen kangoeroes‚Ä¶ en dat terwijl men niet eens weet hoeveel kangoeroes de bosbranden overleefd hebben!

Uw merk heeft bloed aan zijn handen.

Mag ik u daarom vragen om net zoals Diadora en Versace op te houden met het gebruik van kangoeroeleder?
Als marktleider kan u door uw beleid aan te passen een heel grote impact hebben.

Met vriendelijke groeten

Dear sir/madam,

I was informed by the Belgian animal rights organisation GAIA that Adidas still uses kangaroo leather. I am surprised and disappointed.

Kangaroo hunting occurs during the night, from great distances, on moving targets. Shots that do not result in instantaneous death are inevitable. Because hunters often fail to kill the animal immediately, gunshot wounds cause a great deal of suffering. Injured animals sometimes manage to escape and are condemned to long agony. Worse still, bullets can hit the throat, jaw, nose or ears.

Despite the recent forest fires in Australia, kangaroo hunting continues. The hunting quota for 2020 has been set at 6 million kangaroos... even though we do not know how many kangaroos survived the forest fires!

Adidas has blood on its hands.

Can I therefore ask that Adidas, like Diadora and Versace, stops using kangaroo leather? As a market leader Adidas can have a very big impact by adapting their policy.

Kind regards

Generally, I like Nike and have been happy with their products, but I have to put this out there so you know about their customer service.

I purchased a pair of Nike's about a year ago and wear them mostly for travel. After about a year of limited use, the Nike sign started to peel off the sides of the shoe, which was very disappointing. I sent them in to be reviewed through a Nike claim, and although it was a manufacturers flaw, they would not refund or give any sort of compensation for the defect.

I wanted the shoes returned if Nike ‚Ä¢ would not cover the flaw, but also decided that I would submit them to their recycle program if the flaw was covered.

The flaw was not covered, and instead of sending the shoes back to me, they put them into their recycle program anyway and said that there was no way that they could return them to me. So not only are my perfectly good Nike's not being returned to me, but Nike has refused to do anything about this to compensate me for the loss of my shoes.

I am very disappointed in both the quality of this product and the customer service of Nike in this situation. Being such a large company you think they could do something.

Just know that customer service is important, and if you don't treat your customers well, they'll talk about it and not come return.

Their reply to ‚ÄúJust do it‚Äù was ‚ÄúThey Did It‚Äù. Their sacrifice, killed in action from Improvised Explosive Devices, gave Mr. Kapernek permission to kneel on the job. Maybe your marketing strategy will pay off and bring in more profit than you can use or maybe the children, spouses, parents, sisters, brothers of the American military will choose Adidas, New Balance, Saucony, Brooks. Your profit will never equal their commitment.

post_text:
Shalane Flanagan.
After years of medals earned on the world stage, and a grueling 9-month injury recovery, her legacy is cemented on the streets of NYC, as the first American woman in 40 years to win the #TCSNYCMarathon.

Geoffrey Kamworor.
Made his mark in the mud as a world cross country champion. Took to the track for titles won. Turned to the roads to face the world‚Äôs best in the marathon. And set a blistering pace on the concrete of NYC, to capture his first major marathon victory.

Congratulations Shalane Flanagan and Geoffrey Kamworor on your triumphant breakthrough victories in NYC.

I purchased a pair of Nike's about a year ago and wear them mostly for travel. After about a year of limited use, the Nike sign started to peel off the sides of the shoe, which was very disappointing. comment_text: Matt purchased for me a pair of Nike Airmax size 7Y Purple/Grey sneakers. I had owned a pair the year before and they were great. Lasted the whole year, which included a pregnancy weight gain and a lot of walking at work. So, when he asked me the end of that year what I wanted for Christmas, I naturally asked for another pair. However, the second pair became useless after three months of normal wear and tear. No longer pregnant, 50 lbs lighter, and doing the same amount of walking at work that I did the previous year, I couldn't believe what happened. The sole underneath wore way too quickly and then without warning one day as I was walking down the hallway at work, the left sneaker sole that was filled with air ( Hence, the name Airmax) popped and deflated. I nearly lost my balance and fell on my face. Shocked and very disappointed I contacted my fianc√©, but he couldn't find the receipt. So I decided to contact Nike Corporate directly. I told them what had happened and how disappointed I was because I had own the same sneaker the year before without issue. I filed a claim and sent them back the product to take a look. After about two weeks, i received the sneakers back in the mail. With a letter stating that they cannot refund or exchange the product because it was due to normal wear and tear damage or excessive use. Normal wear and tear? Excessive use? What? I contacted them again and asked if they had taken the time frame of three months into account. They said that it was noted, but that their decision is final. I use the sneakers mostly for work. "I only walk", I said, ‚ÄúI don't run or jog or exercise in them." I was still told that their decision is final. Even if I walked in my sleep, excessive use for only three months should not damage a product so expensive as to render it completely useless. Matt says he paid $ 169.00 for my gift. Now he is out $169.00 and I am out of a good pair of sneakers for work. What really gets me is all the claims about this product that they make regarding durability, comfort, traction and performance. Supposedly that is why the sneaker is so costly. And yet, after three months of, what I and many of my family and friends consider normal walking, the sneakers are garbage now. $ 169.00 garbage!!!

comment_text: Matt purchased for me a pair of Nike Airmax size 7Y Purple/Grey sneakers. I had owned a pair the year before and they were great. Lasted the whole year, which included a pregnancy weight gain and a lot of walking at work. So, when he asked me the end of that year what I wanted for Christmas, I naturally asked for another pair. However, the second pair became useless after three months of normal wear and tear. No longer pregnant, 50 lbs lighter, and doing the same amount of walking at work that I did the previous year, I couldn't believe what happened. The sole underneath wore way too quickly and then without warning one day as I was walking down the hallway at work, the left sneaker sole that was filled with air ( Hence, the name Airmax) popped and deflated. I nearly lost my balance and fell on my face. Shocked and very disappointed I contacted my fianc√©, but he couldn't find the receipt. So I decided to contact Nike Corporate directly. I told them what had happened and how disappointed I was because I had own the same sneaker the year before without issue. I filed a claim and sent them back the product to take a look. After about two weeks, i received the sneakers back in the mail. With a letter stating that they cannot refund or exchange the product because it was due to normal wear and tear damage or excessive use. Normal wear and tear? Excessive use? What? I contacted them again and asked if they had taken the time frame of three months into account. They said that it was noted, but that their decision is final. I use the sneakers mostly for work. "I only walk", I said, ‚ÄúI don't run or jog or exercise in them." I was still told that their decision is final. What really gets me is all the claims about this product that they make regarding durability, comfort, traction and performance. Supposedly that is why the sneaker is so costly. comment_text: Matt purchased for me a pair of Nike Airmax size 7Y Purple/Grey sneakers. I had owned a pair the year before and they were great. Lasted the whole year, which included a pregnancy weight gain and a lot of walking at work. So, when he asked me the end of that year what I wanted for Christmas, I naturally asked for another pair. However, the second pair became useless after three months of normal wear and tear. No longer pregnant, 50 lbs lighter, and doing the same amount of walking at work that I did the previous year, I couldn't believe what happened. The sole underneath wore way too quickly and then without warning one day as I was walking down the hallway at work, the left sneaker sole that was filled with air ( Hence, the name Airmax) popped and deflated. I nearly lost my balance and fell on my face. Shocked and very disappointed I contacted my fianc√©, but he couldn't find the receipt. So I decided to contact Nike Corporate directly. I told them what had happened and how disappointed I was because I had own the same sneaker the year before without issue. I filed a claim and sent them back the product to take a look. After about two weeks, i received the sneakers back in the mail. With a letter stating that they cannot refund or exchange the product because it was due to normal wear and tear damage or excessive use. Normal wear and tear? Excessive use? What? I contacted them again and asked if they had taken the time frame of three months into account. They said that it was noted, but that their decision is final. I use the sneakers mostly for work. "I only walk", I said, ‚ÄúI don't run or jog or exercise in them." I was still told that their decision is final. Even if I walked in my sleep, excessive use for only three months should not damage a product so expensive as to render it completely useless. Matt says he paid $ 169.00 for my gift. Now he is out $169.00 and I am out of a good pair of sneakers for work. What really gets me is all the claims about this product that they make regarding durability, comfort, traction and performance. Supposedly that is why the sneaker is so costly. And yet, after three months of, what I and many of my family and friends consider normal walking, the sneakers are garbage now. $ 169.00 garbage!!!

Pete Sampras didn‚Äôt start as the best serve and volley player of his generation.

He had to take that from Pete Sampras.

Maria Sharapova didn‚Äôt reach success by sticking to the status quo.
She changed the game with her style and tenacity.

He made it his, five consecutive times.

Serena Williams wasn‚Äôt born the world‚Äôs number one.
She had to take down the best in the world first.

No one will give you what is theirs.

So to be the next big thing.

The new poster boy.

You‚Äôre going to have to take it from them.

He dominated in neon brights.

Pete Sampras didn‚Äôt start as the best serve and volley player of his generation.
He proved it to all who came before him.

Roger Federer wasn‚Äôt always the record holder of major wins.
He had to take that from Pete Sampras.

Maria Sharapova didn‚Äôt reach success by sticking to the status quo.
She changed the game with her style and tenacity.

Rafael Nadal wasn‚Äôt simply given the longest winning streak of any tournament.
He made it his, five consecutive times.

Serena Williams wasn‚Äôt born the world‚Äôs number one.
She had to take down the best in the world first.

No one will give you what is theirs.

The talk of the town.
The new poster boy.

comment_text:
Dear Sir / Madam,

I was in your Burwood, Sydney store on Saturday and made a purchase
my transaction Ref: 453043 at 1:29pm.

I asked a sales assistant about a yoga mat and was shown the stock
and I decided to buy it.

She leaves it on the counter and asks another sales assistant to process the transaction.

Whilst I stood waiting for a few minutes while different staff members were having conversations
with each other, more time goes by and then I see what looks to the manager standing behind the counter
having a good old chat to another sales assistant, as a waiting customer, I was absolutely irate!

I asked the sales assistant: Are you going to ring this up? To which she proceeded to do.

I was so incensed at what had just happened, the bopping of the sales assistants heads to the music,
chatting with other colleagues, whilst a paying customer was left standing there like a lump...
I forgot my package which I had just picked up from the Post Office and my black leather Zegna wallet.

Being so disgusted and irritated, I left the shop without realizing it, my mistake: yes, but, it must be somewhere...
Where is it?

I returned on Sunday about 5:30pm to ask a blonde haired lady who said she was the manager:

When I asked her "did somebody hand this in or is there a lost and found?"
she gave me a black look and replied that they didn't / haven't.

Then some macho stocky staff member told me that I should ask the Conceirge of Westfields... What!?
When I said to him: if it was found in the store, you would have a record of it,
and, why, would you take it to the concierge?

This outraged me again!!! Is he taking the piss or what!?

It boils down to this, I picked up my package from the Post Office before 1pm
did some shopping and left the Nike store without my package and wallet:
and YOU HAVE CCTV FOOTAGE OF WHO TOOK IT.

I demand that footage be released to me or to Burwood Police!

I want a phone call Monday morning, and to updated with all proceedings, or I'll be ringing Burwood Police station,
on social media, ringing 2UE, 2GB, emailing and phoning Today Tonight and ACA about a company that doesn't pay it's taxes
in Australia and employees that steal from customers, right before Christmas time.

Sincerely,

Ashley Smith
xxxx xxx xxx
